tweet: 6/ As a matter of fact, our delegates can and do vote differently than we do, which we think is healthy and a sign of a strong community where different voices are heard. The recent @Uniswap vote is just one example. https://t.co/gae1Wj0Q4t

name: Kathryn Haun
tweet: 5/ To truly unlock the benefits of decentralization, a strong form of delegation is needed—one that enhances the quality & diversity of the governing body & perhaps *most importantly* one that empowers each delegate to vote independently from the token holder.

name: Kathryn Haun
tweet: 4/ Why is that? In our experience backing the most promising crypto projects, we view delegation as a powerful way to expand the number of participants who have a meaningful say in the governance process & seed the development of a high-quality governing body over the long term

name: Kathryn Haun
tweet: 3/ Crypto is about removing gatekeepers. This requires stakeholders like us to think critically as to our role in the process and how we can best contribute to protocol governance. While there are many ways we look to do so, we are strong proponents of token delegation.

name: Kathryn Haun
tweet:
2/ We've continued to refine that framework. Today, we’re sharing more information about our core governance principles including new details about the delegation program we pioneered beginning well over a year ago that @_jamico now helps run full-time.

https://t.co/d6kR66U7mF

tweet: 9/ The U.S. should have a proactive, affirmative vision for how we will remain the tech epicenter of the world. The amendment offered by @RonWyden @SenLummis & @SenToomey helps us have that conversation beyond this legislation.

name: Kathryn Haun
tweet: 8/ That said, the crypto universe extends far beyond its financial origins. Smart regs must reflect the nuance that different crypto uses will require different rules of the road. That’s how the U.S. will capture economic & societal benefits from this computing wave.

name: Kathryn Haun

name: Kathryn Haun
tweet: 5/ These new social networks, games, art & ecommerce applications are exciting bc they shift power to people and creators and away from centralized platforms. These protocols will continue to be developed by teams around the world—regardless of what the U.S. does.

name: Kathryn Haun
tweet: 3/ This amounts to the US government placing its thumb on the scale to choose winners and losers very early in the development of a nascent technology movement and would undoubtedly open the infra bill up to future legal challenges. This is policymaking at its absolute worst.

tweet: 6/ And even where the legacy system “works” and financial institutions flag suspected illicit conduct, the govt is often still not particularly effective at stopping it (as the recent FinCEN files fiasco demonstrates) https://t.co/UWmSzVkO6X

name: Kathryn Haun
tweet: 5/ In fact, the current legacy financial system fails to prevent illicit finance & money laundering 99.9% of the time https://t.co/9dlB57gu7D. https://t.co/PXfXaaeCF3. As @ChuckGrassley put it, the system is just one decimal point away from total failure

name: Kathryn Haun
tweet: 4/ Not only those in the crypto industry think this. Many with decades of law enforcement & natl security experience have shared that the proposed rules won't really help their mission of stopping illicit finance, and worse, only threaten to put the US behind in crypto innovation

name: Kathryn Haun
tweet: 3/ Late yesterday, instead of following that process, @stevenmnuchin1 slashed the ordinary comment period to just 15 days, on a Friday before the holidays no less, for crypto regulations that to us @a16z and others in the crypto space don’t make much sense

name: Kathryn Haun
tweet: 2/ In fact, agencies are encouraged to consider a longer comment period for complex areas. The global and distributed nature of crypto is nothing if not complex. The reason for this amount of time is simple: it’s about due process. The opportunity to be meaningfully heard.

name: Kathryn Haun
tweet: 1/ There’s a reason the regulatory rulemaking process provides 30-60 days for notice & comment. So that those outside govt - consumers, industry, public interest orgs, academics, etc - have a meaningful opportunity to weigh in & provide viewpoints govt may not have considered
